@@eThe Khephari: Those Who Roll the World Forward@@N

@@dFrom the geological survey notes of Keeper Road Warden Torvald,@@N
@@dwith annotations by an unnamed Khephari stonecutter@@N

Massive. Chitinous. Patient beyond any measure that human calendars
can express. The Khephari are scarab-beetle folk whose shells shine
like worked bronze in the sun and darken to deep umber in shadow.
They stand a full head above most humans, and their weight is
considerable — a Khephari walks and the ground @@yknows it@@N.

Their theology is simple and total: @@ethe cycle does not stop@@N.
Decay and renewal are not opposites. They are the same process,
observed at different moments. What rots feeds what grows. What
crumbles becomes the foundation for what rises. The Khephari do
not mourn ruins. They @@ybuild on them@@N.

Every Khephari has died once. The @@emolting transformation@@N — when
the juvenile shell cracks and the adult form emerges — is understood
as a true death and rebirth. The pain is extraordinary. The memory
of the old self persists but is no longer sovereign. Rare elders
survive a @@rsecond molting@@N, and what emerges is something the
other peoples have learned to treat with considerable respect.

They speak to the ground. Vibration-sensing organs in their feet
read the deep language of stone and soil — @@eearth-speech@@N, they
call it. They feel the tremors that precede quakes, the slow groan
of settling bedrock, the hollow resonance of buried chambers. When
a Khephari tells you the ground is unhappy, @@ylisten@@N.

They built the roads. Not all of them — but the roads to and from
the @@eGreat Pyramid@@N are Khephari work, and those roads have not
shifted in centuries. Human roads crack. Khephari roads @@yremember
where they are supposed to be@@N.

When the @@rCinderteeth@@N began to stir, it was the Khephari who
filed seismic warnings with the Keeper survey offices. Detailed
readings. Precise timelines. Recommendations for evacuation. The
warnings were received, logged, and filed without action. The
Khephari do not speak of this with bitterness. They speak of it
with the flat certainty of a people who have learned that
@@dinstitutions read what they choose to read@@N.

They do not need acknowledgment. Their work is in the stone, and
the stone does not forget.

@@dThe road remembers. The beetle endures.@@N
